Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of sales tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
preface
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the Court of Auditors have the power to audit the entire public finances.
The statement requires the Court of Auditors to have the power to scrutinise tax collection as much as possible.
The Organisation of Europe's Top Audit Authorities (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VI EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenues by the Court of Auditors.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activities of a Court of Auditors is the development of a specific strategy for auditing public revenue.
This is especially true for taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies become increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation may arise in which national auditors carry out their audit activities only in cooperation with the auditors of other countries. to be able to.
As an example, the examination of internationally organized fraud may be considered, which can lead to significant loss of revenue in many states.
Cooperation between the authorities is needed to combat such offences.
Auditors who scrutinise this area must be prepared to work closely with each other.
The idea for an audit of VAT as well as the MIAS system was born at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Office.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating Court of Auditors first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of VAT management in the Czech Republic and Germany.
Based on the analysis of the available information, we made the selection of the examination subject-matter for the audit planning.
Achieving the efficient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual states (in particular EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT, and Creating greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only contribute to improving the work of financial management, but can also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of sales tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Introduction
Case number: CZ) 06/27 (DE) VIII 2 – 2005 – 1215
Examining subject:
(CZ) Management of VAT after Czech Republic joins the European Union
(DE) Audit on the cooperation of administrative authorities in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004
The Commission's audit target:
(CZ) The aim of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures used by the financial administration in the field of VAT following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (' EC '). ) with free movement of goods and services and the use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community deliveries.
(DE) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control, with a focus on administrative assistance in the area of VAT in accordance with the above regulations.
As a result of the audit, vulnerabilities should be identified and recommendations should be made to address them.
VAT information exchange system The audits were jointly carried out by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NKcomo") and the Federal Court of Justice ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany as a result of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006. Performed.
The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of international administrative assistance between the financial administrations. Information and comparison of VAT management systems in the two states.
A joint final report on the results of the examinations was prepared in line with European Guideline 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards.
The period audited covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of results and evaluation of parallel audit
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two Court yards.
In addition to the focus on "exchange of information" in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004 of the Commission, other closely related aspects were also examined, such as the registration of taxpayers, tax returns and summary summaries. Messages.
In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation for cross-border passenger transport by bus and bus and coach comparisons.
When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two states, differences were found in the following areas:
1) Registration for sales tax purposes.
While in Germany the entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the main criterion for registration is the exceeding of the revenue threshold set out in the VAT Act.
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers receive only a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community sales.
In Germany, the taxpayer receives a tax number valid only for domestic sales for the purposes of sales tax.
If the German taxpayer wants to make intra-Community transactions, he must apply for the issuance of a special identification number, the so-called USt-IdNr.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be standardised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach is tax-free, but there is a right to deduct input tax.
In Germany, the transport service, as far as the route passes through Germany, is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to unify the situation in accordance with Article 393 of Directive 2006/112/EC of the Council of 28 November 2006 on the Common VAT System (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic taxpayers only have to file VAT returns for underyear tax periods (month or quarter), taxpayers in Germany (monthly or quarterly) have
Sales tax pre-registrations and a sales tax declaration after the end of the calendar year.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, taxpayers in Germany have to submit the VAT pre-registrations electronically.
The introduction of the obligation to file VAT returns in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech financial administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary messages.
While taxpayers in the Czech Republic are required to submit their summary reports to the tax offices (FIS), German taxpayers must submit the summary reports to the CLO2.
Accordingly, the information from the summary reports is available to the FIS in the Czech Republic immediately after they have been submitted.
The information from the summary reports is only available after they have been processed by the CLO.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community sales is needed as promptly as possible.
The monthly submission of summary messages would shorten the period between the time of sales and the updating of MIAS data.
This would allow for a timely examination of taxation in the buyer's Member State (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same time limits.
5) International exchange of information in the area of VAT.
In the case of requests for information, the Czech CLO monitors compliance with the three-month period.
The German CLO does not monitor processing times.
As a result, the German financial administration has completed a significantly lower percentage of requests for information received within the specified time limit.
Because of these problems, the BRH has recommended constant monitoring of deadlines for the German CLO (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is in the process of developing its own risk management system (RMS) with appropriate strengths and weaknesses.
The NKcomo and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches to an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5).
As part of the cooperation, the two Court of Auditors examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions carried out between Czech and German tax entities.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed by using the legal options of the CLO, where there were doubts about the correct taxation or suspicions of VAT fraud.
The Court of Auditors found that:
In some cases, the FIS used the information obtained in the international exchange of information and redefined the VAT liability of the taxpayers concerned.
In those cases, taxpayers had either unlawfully taken advantage of the VAT exemption or had not reported the purchase of goods in their VAT return.
In some cases, the FIS could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal requirements in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial management of another Member State refused to provide information requested.
Some cases have been uncovered where taxpayers misreported sales in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in MIAS were therefore incorrect, requiring the caseworkers (the FIS) to investigate in these cases (see 6).
