Registration of taxpayers in Germany
In accordance with the provisions of the Tax Regulations (§ § 137, 138 AO), each business operation must be registered with the municipality and/or the relevant tax office.
This application must be made no later than one month after commencement of business.
The municipality forwards the registration to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office determines that a business activity has started but has not been registered, it may also register taxpayers retrospectively on its own initiative.
In Germany, taxpayers, regardless of whether they are resident or non-resident, are obliged to register for Zwekke of the sales tax if they meet the requirements in § 2 of the German VAT Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the amount of revenue generated.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Special FIS are responsible for entrepreneurs based abroad.
For example, the FA ChemnitzSouth is responsible for those entrepreneurs based in the Czech Republic.
On 30 April 2004, 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered with it; On 1 March 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there.
According to the findings of the BRH, these FIS with special responsibilities often refused to register so-called bogus self-employed persons residing in the new central and central property. Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since, after the accession of these ten countries, the free movement of workers is still restricted, these self-employed persons tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These (sham) self-employed persons do not meet the requirements set out in § 2 of the UStG for recognition as an entrepreneur, since they are usually dependent on a single client who determines their working hours and the type of work execution.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must complete a questionnaire from the relevant FA and provide information about the company and the business activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a mandatory pre-print for all FIS in Germany.
It is processed either in special organizational units within the FIS or in the organizational units generally responsible for the tax assessment.
This prepression is used to carry out a risk assessment for the individual taxpayer prior to the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic sales is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the relevant FA, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, The following five (or four) digits are the identification feature for the taxpayer, the last digit Is always a control figure.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he needs a USt-IdNr in order to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries.
This is allocated by the CLO on request if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for VAT purposes.
The USt-IdNr. Automatically allocated by the CLO is when the taxpayer declares intra-Community deliveries in their VAT pre-registrations or in their annual sales tax declaration.
The USt-IdNr. Consist of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (e.g. if he ceases to do business), but only after processing all tax transactions (predisposition of all financial years) or 2. if the financial administration determines that he has no Business more operates.
As a rule, the validity of the USt-IdNr depends. The validity of the VAT number.
In these cases, the FIS must inform the CLO of the deletion of the VAT number, so that the validity of the VAT ID number there. Can be terminated at this time.
According to the Value Added Tax Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic taxpayers do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. The turnover of the previous calendar year plus the resulting sales tax did not exceed the amount of €17,500 and will be 2nd The following year probably does not exceed the amount of €50,000.
The so-called small business owners are not entitled to charge other entrepreneurs sales tax, nor for the pretax deduction.
Although they don't have to pay sales tax, small business owners are required to register with the Tax Office and file an annual sales tax return.
A small business owner may declare the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the next five years.
He is then allowed to charge the sales tax and deduct the input tax.
Non-resident taxpayers can appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that they only make tax-free sales and waive the deduction.
The fiscal representative fulfils the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so that he does not have to register for sales tax purposes.
The invoices indicate that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is the exceeding of the threshold amount mentioned in the VAT Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardized, but differences can occur due to different organizational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the taxpayer will receive a tax number at the time of his first registration for any tax.
In the case of its registration for VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community sales.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for sales tax purposes receives a tax number exclusively for intra-German sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community sales, he must specifically allocate a USt-IdNr. to apply for.
Both the NKcomo and the BRH noted that the German two-tier registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which has a single identification number for both national registration for VAT and Generating intra-Community sales can lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows retrospective (national registration) in cases where the taxpayer does not register his business with the municipality or the relevant FA.
This retroactive registration allows for a correct predisposition to sales tax for previous investment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the VAT liability.
As the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules for the whole of the EC should be standardised.
The German parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Office for Taxes to every natural person after birth.
This number applies to individuals residing in Germany for life.
If a natural person takes up business, the relevant FA applies for a commercial tax identification number, which is known as VAT ID No. Serves.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a taxpayer and the allocation of the USt-IdNr. To give.
Work to implement an IT process for managing numbers is ongoing.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach
The legal requirements in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of Section 70 of Law No. 235/2004, the transport of passengers between the individual Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and it exists since 1 May 2004. Entitlement to pre-tax deduction.
The exemption from VAT also applies if the transport is carried out by persons registered as taxpayers in other Member States or by foreigners liable to tax domestically.
The return journey is considered a separate transport process.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not engage in any economic activity other than cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach, they are not obliged to act as subject to VAT in the Czech Republic To register.
Cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic was excluded from VAT liability as a result of the Law on Accession of the Czech Republic Annex No. V, Chapter 5 (1) (b). The listed body states in the wording:
"For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77/388/EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with paragraph 17 in Annex F of the Directive, maintain the tax exemption for cross-border passenger transport either until the requirement of the Article 28 (4) of the Directive is complied with or as long as the same tax exemption is applied by any of the current Member States. "
The legal requirements in Germany
According to Article 46 of Directive 2006/112/EG of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by § 3b (1) UStG, a transport service is carried out where the transport is effected.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the part of the transport service attributable to the country is subject to taxation in Germany.
German taxation also does not distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident taxpayer promotes persons through Germany, the part of the transport attributable to Germany is considered a taxable transport.
Before providing his services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the relevant FA.
This registers him for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and grants a special certificate for each bus of strength mentioned in the taxpayer's application.
The entrepreneur must state his taxable transport services in a German VAT return.
As of 1 March 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the FA Chemnitz-Süd.
If the transport service is provided to a domestically resident entrepreneur, the non-resident taxpayer does not have to pay the sales tax to the FA himself.
In its place, the domestic buyer of the services must pay the sales tax to the tax office and the net amount charged to the non-resident taxpayer. This process is known as the "shift in tax liability" and is in line with Article 196 of Directive 2006/112/EC of the Council.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident taxpayer and his income tax return, the German financial administration has several means of examining the accuracy of the tax return with regard to taxable personal transport:
Customs mobile control groups check the certificates of buses and coaches registered abroad, which are used for passenger transport through Germany.
After each audit, the mobile control groups submit an inspection protocol to the relevant FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group can require the bus driver to pay VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident taxpayer can deduct the sales tax paid in this way from the tax liability stated in his sales tax return.
If the FA has doubts as to the accuracy of a VAT return, it may order an audit to be carried out in the FA or use the administrative assistance funds referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxpayer refuses to pay the legally fixed VAT, the FA may request administrative assistance under Council Directive 76/308/EEC.
The BRH considers these means of administrative assistance in tax matters to verify the VAT return or compliance with the tax liability by a non-resident bus operator to be too burdensome in relation to the small amount of revenue from the sales tax on Taxable passenger transport.
In particular, the examination of a non-resident taxpayer's books incurs disproportionately high costs for the taxpayer himself and for the financial administration.
The latter must examine the foreign books, which requires not only knowledge of the foreign language, but also of foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an audit is expected to result in a higher amount of time than for a resident taxpayer, although the audit is limited to the personal transport carried out in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must accept not only the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States insofar as he carries out personal promotions there.
In addition, for each Member State in which even a single person is transported, the taxpayer must have all existing tax obligations in the various languages and on the basis of the forms of the financial administrations of the relevant Member State. EC Member States.
Thus, the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services leads to a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation varies between the two countries.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between various EC Member States and between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT under the Czech Republic's accession law.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT in accordance with the route of transport generated by German territory.
If a non-resident taxpayer provides such a transport service for the first time, he must register this with the relevant FA beforehand.
The taxpayer registers the taxpayer who has to declare the taxable share of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
Law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech taxpayers registered with the FA Chemnitz-South have the transport of persons as their business purpose.
The tax revenue in question is quite low in relation to administrative expenses.
Member States – levy VAT under Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112/EG of 28 November 2006 on the common VAT system – have a high administrative burden relative to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionately high cost of VAT, cross-border passenger transport should only be taxable in one Member State.
This could be the state where promotion begins or where the care provider is based.
Such a form of taxation would call for an amendment to the Council's Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006.
VAT returns
Delivery and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Unless otherwise determined by the law, even if no tax liability has been incurred, the entrepreneur is in charge of filing a VAT return on the requirement set by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the expiry of the tax period. Committed.
The tax liability arises at the expiry of the deadline for filing the VAT return. The exception to this scheme is, in accordance with Law No. 235/2004, the VAT on the import of goods. This is where the due date of the tax is determined by customs rules.
If, as a result, there is an above-average deductible input entitlement, this amount will be refunded to the taxpayer within 30 days of this deduction being set, without any application being drawn up for it must.
The deadline is not applied in cases where the Treasury officer initiates a tax procedure regarding the taxpayer's tax liability.
Pursuant to Section 73 (11) of Law No. 235/2004, the right to deduct input tax may be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the entitlement to pre-tax deduction was created.
After this period, the deduction of input tax can still be claimed within three years of the end of the tax period in which the assertion would have been possible for the first time.
For this, however, a supplementary VAT return is required.
An amendment to Law No. 235/2004, which came into force on 1 January 2005, allows a supplementary VAT return to be made only for the period in which the entitlement to deductions for VAT could have been asserted for the first time.
A taxpayer must file a supplementary VAT return if: (a) the sum of the adjustments leads to an increase in the tax liability, (b) he makes adjustments which do not alter the recently known tax liability, but only previous ones Details are amended (c) he makes adjustments to the VAT rate and tax liability in accordance with Section 49 of Law No. 235/2004.
A taxpayer can file a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the adjustments reduces the tax liability.
