Delivery and processing of VAT returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly VAT pre-registrations and the annual VAT return.
Those taxpayers who are required to submit VAT advance registrations will still have to submit an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners who are not required to pay sales tax must file an annual sales tax return.
Taxpayers are generally obliged to submit a VAT pre-registration by the end of the calendar quarter in which the sales tax is incurred (§ 18 (2) UStG).
However, if the VAT liability is fraud in the previous year more than €6,136 or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is obliged to submit monthly VAT pre-registrations no later than the 10th day after the end of the month in question.
The taxpayer can also opt for the filing of monthly VAT pre-registrations if he has been reimbursed in the previous year for an amount of €6,136 (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual sales tax has not exceeded €512, neither VAT pre-registrations nor VAT returns must be issued.
A resulting VAT liability must be paid 10 days after the end of the tax period.
A refund may result in a more thorough audit by the financial administration.
(Legal) There are no deadlines for processing VAT returns and for refunding VAT overpayments.
In order to receive a timely refund, security can be offered for the refund amount.
In principle, VAT returns, including reimbursement cases, must be processed quickly.
The German VAT Act allows these (levy or payment) deadlines to be extended (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the delivery of the VAT pre-registrations as well as the corresponding payments may be made one month later. In the case of monthly notifications, however, a special prepayment must be made for this.
This payment will be offset against the VAT liability found for the pre-registration period in December.
If an error is discovered, the entrepreneur must submit a corrected VAT pre-registration.
There is no "supplementary" VAT return.
Once the VAT return to be filed by 31 May of the following year has been submitted to the tax office, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect VAT pre-registration, but only the incorrect annual VAT return.
Adjustments of this VAT return to the benefit or disadvantage of the taxpayer are possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT return was filed.
After this four-year period expires, a sales tax return can usually only be corrected in cases of frivolous tax shortening or tax evasion.
Taxpayers must submit the VAT pre-registrations electronically.
The FIS may grant exceptions to this rule to avoid unreasonable hardship.
The annual VAT return can be submitted either in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the levy is made without certification, the taxpayer must make the declaration on additional paper and with his personal signature.
If no pre-sales tax applications or declarations are submitted, the financial administration is entitled to provide a rough estimate of the revenue generated by the taxpayer.
In the event of a late levy, the taxpayer may be subject to a late surcharge (up to 10% of the tax liability or up to €25,000).
In an earlier examination, the BRH found that the FIS often did not charge this delay.
In cases where the fee collected the delay surcharges, the amount was fixed inconsistently and arbitrarily.
The delay surcharge therefore misses its purpose in reducing the average delay, particularly in the filing of the annual VAT return.
The pre-print of the VAT return contains separate lines for value information on intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions.
There are also separate lines for the purchase of services.
