In Germany, taxpayers must submit their advance applications no later than 10 days, depending on the amount of their tax liability in the previous year, either after the end of the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
The annual VAT declaration must be made by 31 May of the following year at the latest.
The obligation to file an annual VAT return has some advantages and disadvantages:
+ After the end of the calendar year, the taxpayer can correct the errors in the monthly pre-registrations by filing a single VAT return;
– If the taxpayer corrects his information on intra-Community transactions, the correction cannot be assigned to a specific reporting period of the ZM;
– The federal states do not match MIAS data on intra-Community acquisitions of German taxpayers until the VAT annual declarations have been processed.
