The need to set up the special audit units arose from the increase in identified new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly in relation to chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of the tax investigators or focus on taxpayers with certain activities, multinationals and taxpayers with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks in the area of VAT have been integrated into the system ATIS: – the task of "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk-bearing tax returns, – the task of "selecting The taxpayers under audit, "whereby the taxpayers under audit are selected on the basis of certain criteria, – the task of" MIAS, "which allows the finance officials access to the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The task "MIAS" makes the following possible: – check the validity of the USt-IdNr. Taxpayers from other Member States, – confirmation of the value of goods delivered to a Czech taxpayer, as indicated in the ZM by all suppliers of the taxpayer concerned from other Member States, – creation of a List of taxpayers who have not provided ZM – formal control of the information provided to taxpayers in the Czech Republic before these disclosures are transmitted to other Member States, – draw up a list of the Taxpayers in whose VAT returns do not match the information in the ZM on the delivery of goods to other Member States – draw up a list of taxpayers in whose VAT returns provide the information on the value of the Other Member States did not match the information in the ZM of all their suppliers from other Member States.
As part of their responsibility to combat tax evasion, financial officials have access to the data from state authorities such as commercial registers, land registers, motor vehicle registers, commercial registers, etc.
