Risk management in Germany
Because of their federal structure, both the federal financial authorities (especially the CLO) and the financial administrations of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and introduction of an RMS in the Federal Republic of Germany.
Although there are joint working groups for development, neither the CLO nor the financial administrations of the federal states have a uniform data base.
At CLO level, the ST I 2 unit (' KUSS ' – Coordination Unit for Recorded Tax Examinations and Tax Investigation) collects the audit findings on fraud cases in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER was set up in the USS. There, the tax offices can enter and also query the names of discovered Missing Traders or VAT fraudsters.
The KUSS coordinates both related cases of sales tax fraud nationally and cases of cross-border sales tax fraud.
The experience of the KUSS is brought to bear in the development of the RMS through their participation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other CLO and BMF organisational units are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of UStIdNr. Other Member States that appear in the ZM of German taxpayers are carried out by the CLO.
This formal review takes place before the ZM is transmitted to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and thus its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The examination of the validity of the USt-IdNr. The O _ MCTL identifications submitted by the other Member States are carried out on the basis of the O _ MCTL identifications (for the procedure of correcting invalid VAT ID, see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the CLO's RMS relies on the MIAS data provided by the other Member States and generates various types of communications for the discovery of suspected missing traders. Certain characteristics are used as clues, which usually occur in carousel transactions.
The State's officials are instructed to process these communications and must forward the outcome of their investigations to the CLO in certain cases.
The BRH audit has confirmed that all available features must be included in order to infer a case of tax fraud with sufficient probability (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH has recommended that the BMF work with combinations of different indications in the preparation of the messages.
The risk management system should also take into account other indications, such as the taxpayer's payment behaviour, the industry or the company's shareholding relationships.
A second level of risk management exists with the financial administrations of the federal states and focuses on the processing of VAT pre-registrations and annual declarations.
For example, the system compiles a list of those taxpayers who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their VAT pre-registration or declaration of the annual financial year.
This list will be sent to the CLO to monitor the full submission of the ZM.
Furthermore, this type of risk management compares the purchases indicated by the taxpayer in his annual VAT return with the data in MIAS.
The financial administrations of the federal states avoid comparing the quarterly data, as these would result in too many inconsistencies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; Such as.:
– Supplier and purchaser assume different times for the execution of intra-Community turnover;
– different accounting collection and tax explanation of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the data from the VAT returns with the MIAS data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms based on data in the VAT returns and certain other indications (e.g. Company words, age of the owner partner, number of employees and payment method of the taxpayer).
Bavaria has introduced a fixed rules-based risk management system that allows a team of anti-tax fraud specialists (' risk managers ') to programme their own rules so that suspected tax fraudsters Filtered out.
This system is used in the processing of VAT forecasts by the FIS.
This gives the relevant FA the guidance of the RMS before the sales tax is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, risk managers must adjust the rules according to feedback from the FIS.
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data uncovered in the rear of the background.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics for tax evasion.
The system compiles a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent subjects decide on the examination of the taxpayers concerned.
After the audit, tax auditors must report their findings so that the RMS can learn from the results of the exams it proposes.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rules-based fuzzy system.
Based on a lot of data from processed sales tax returns and some other clues, this neuro-fuzzy system (also called a data-mining system) calculates how likely a taxpayer is to be mired in tax fraud.
After that, it creates a monthly list of suspected tax cheats.
Based on this list, the FIS select the taxpayers in question for examination and report the exam results to the data center in question.
The introduction of these three RMS is under way in the federal states.
Because each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems seems purposeful.
Whether the hoped-for effects will materialize with the actual use remains to be seen.
Comparison and evaluation
While it is not possible in this report to deal with the specific criteria of RMS in the Czech and German, the NKcomo and BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three German states mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud – carousel fraud in particular – has proved to be a problem not a national but a European one.
The people involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one Member State, but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches to an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State. Failure to do so, fraudsters choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their offences.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is located.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud may be affected.
That is why there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
