In his Czech sales tax return, he did not report sales tax on the sale of goods in Germany.
Due to a supplementary VAT return issued after the external audit, the Czech finance official set the VAT liability unchanged.
Under Czech legislation, there was no purchase of goods from other Member States in this case, as the goods were not shipped or transported from another Member State to the Czech Republic.
Thus, the Czech finance official drew a wrong conclusion during the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the response to the request for information, which showed that the goods had not left Germany, the German taxpayer's tax return corrected and the payment of Sales tax worth €1,600.
In addition, the relevant FA sent a control notice to the FA responsible for the actual recipient of the goods to ensure that the resale of those goods was properly taxed.
In the following cases, entrepreneurs declared intra-Community deliveries that may not have been carried out:
18th.
The Czech Finance Officer received a request for information from the German tax authorities on the question of whether the Czech taxpayer had purchased a car worth €47,400 from the German taxpayer in February 2005.
As an attachment, the request for information was accompanied by an imprint of the Czech taxpayer's VAT registration certificate.
As a further facility, a photocopy of the passport was attached to the person who was supposed to have transferred the vehicle.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech finance official found that the passport had been stolen, that the person named in it had not imported a vehicle into the Czech Republic and stated that he had no contacts with a German taxpayer.
The VAT registration certificate, the imprint of which had been sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech Financial Administration.
With this information, the Czech finance official replied to the request for information and at the same time stated that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
By request to the local Czech finance official, the NKcomo stated that the Czech taxpayer is not based at the address specified in the Commercial Register and that the managing director of the company is not reachable.
Following a tax complaint procedure for the tax period February 2005, the Czech finance official set the tax liability of the Czech taxpayer with zero.
In the course of further investigation, the Czech finance official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had acquired it based on an internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local German finance official had rejected the German taxpayer's claim to exempt this delivery from VAT on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the goods purchased in the VAT return and the reported values from other Member States.
A Czech taxpayer was said to have delivered €89,424 worth of goods to a German taxpayer in the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005.
Since the acquisition declared by the German taxpayer did not comply with the MIAS data, the German finance official requested the verification of deliveries and their payment as part of the intergovernmental exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech finance official stated that the only managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the Commercial Register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was allegedly a relative of the Czech company's shareholder.
The Czech taxpayer issued a VAT return and an ZM signed after the cancellation of the managing director in the Commercial Register by a person not authorised to do so, namely that shareholder of the company.
The accountant of the Czech taxpayer informed the tax officer that the owner of the capital had paid the payment for the goods charged into the company's account in euros.
Box office receipts were not issued.
By request from the local Czech FA, the CFO found that the Czech taxpayer's entitlement to VAT exemption for goods deliveries to other Member States worth 1.326.307 CZK in the first quarter of 2004 and Recognized by 1.416.180 CZK in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German finance official did not correct the German acquirer's VAT return, as in the meantime a German court had upheld the German taxpayer's insolvency.
Since the earlier external audit showed no evidence of tax fraud, there was no prospect of actually being able to levy a fixed VAT liability.
20. According to the MIAS data, in 2005, a German taxpayer acquired goods from the Czech Republic worth 4.251.196, after which he had purchased goods worth €43,274 the previous year.
The German taxpayer did not declare the intra-Community acquisitions in his 2004 VAT return or in the 2005 return on sales tax.
In addition, he did not declare any output sales corresponding in value terms.
Because of these discrepancies, the German FA made a request for information regarding the fourth quarter of 2005 and the first quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community goods deliveries totalling 167.246.083 CZK.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received in which the German side requested to check whether the delivery reported by the Czech taxpayer had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech Finance Administration stated that the German request could not be complied with because the Czech company did not have a managing director (or other legal representative).
The documents handed over to the NKcomo by the relevant financial officer show that, together with the managing director of the Czech taxpayer, on 30 March 2006, a protocol on the commencement of the VAT audit for the fourth quarter of 2004 and the period From January to December 2005.
At the same time, the taxpayer was asked by the tax officer to provide all accounting and tax documents for this period, but failed to do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the sole managing director expired on 16 May 2005 without a new managing director being appointed.
The Czech taxpayer has not issued VAT tax returns since April 2006.
As part of the parallel audit, the NKcomo, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community deliveries between the Czech Republic and Germany, which were not the subject of prior exchange of information between the two countries. Were.
The two Court of Auditors exchanged information on the audited cases through the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the relevant FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to conduct taxable business in Germany.
Based on this information, the company was registered from June 2005, but did not receive a German USt-IdNr.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the manufacture of wind turbines and for their delivery to Austria in the name, risk and account of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient production capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the contract to a German taxpayer (UDE) based in Germany.
The following figure shows the contractual relations and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to the German legal situation, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
– The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account for assembly.
Because of the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
– Because the carrier was contracted by the Danish company (UDK) and had the latter carry out the transport in its own name, at its own risk and for its own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-entrepreneur (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as liable for taxation in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE), Since the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is different from the seat state of the Czech company.
Accordingly, the delivery is properly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
– The supply of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
– The delivery of the remaining wind turbines manufactured in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria as well as intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community deliveries either in its German tax returns or in its ZM delivered to the German CLO.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all of its intra-Community deliveries uniformly as intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic.
The NKcomo found that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, cooperation between at least four financial administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be required, although in this case there were no signs of Tax fraud or evasion.
In addition, the NKcomo and BRH examined case designs to show the magnitude of the differences caused by the different legislation of 2004 between the data in VAT returns and the MIAS data.
The cases examined also show that it takes some time for taxpayers and the subject to apply the new legal requirements:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech taxpayer reported shipments of goods totalling 792.977.452 CZK to a German taxpayer.
During the same period, another Czech taxpayer reported intra-Community deliveries to another German taxpayer with a total value of 18.157.265 CZK.
The information provided by the BRH to the NKcomo showed that both cases involved electricity deliveries.
Both Czech taxpayers took into account the above deliveries in their ZM in accordance with Czech Law No. 235/2004, which was in force in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of the NKcomo found that in 2004, different legal requirements were in place for the supply or acquisition of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany.
While in the Czech Republic taxpayers will supply electrical energy in accordance with the votes of Law No. Declared as intra-Community goods in 2004, according to the German statutory provisions in force in 2004, it was not an intra-Community purchase of goods, but taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in legal requirements were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law No. 635/2004, which amended some tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. During the examination of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further found that a Czech taxpayer was in his ZM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 intra-Community deliveries to a German Taxpayers with the total value of 240.411.163 CZK and another Czech taxpayer in his ZM declared intra-Community deliveries to another German taxpayer worth 263.470.776 CZK for the same period.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKcomo showed that in both cases they had been deliveries of electrical energy.
According to the wording of Law No. 235/2004, applicable on 1 January 2005, the place of performance in the case of the supply of electrical energy is the one where the purchaser has his legal place, place of business or place of establishment for which this delivery takes place.
That is why the Czech taxpayers should not have reported the supply of electricity in their ZM for 2005.
The fact that both taxpayers treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies led to a equivalent difference of 503.881.939 CZK in MIAS.
Final remark
The cooperation achieved the objectives of the BRH and the NKcomo.
Both Court of Auditors gained in-depth knowledge of VAT management systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences between the two systems and the legal requirements applicable to VAT management.
During the parallel examinations, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions emerged.
For some of them, another observation is worthwhile.
Based on the audit results, both Court Courts developed recommendations for managing VAT.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a control check should be part of further monitoring.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of both Court of Auditors is the basis for the successful implementation of future audits in the area of VAT management.
